nt, or draw on interviews with them, and give firsthand accounts of how klezmer is transmitted and how its practitioners maintain a balance between preservation and innovation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aJewsvMusicvCongresses. 0aJewsxMusicvCongresses. 0aJewsxMusicxCongresses. 0aKlezmer musicvCongresses. 0aKlezmer musicxCongresses. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aamerican history.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  adance music.  afolk music.  afolk musicians.  ahasidic jews.  ahasidism.  ajewish history.  ajewish language.  ajewish studies.  ajewish youth.  ajews.  ajudaism.  aklezmer union.  aklezmer.  amusic genres.  aphiladelphia.  areligion.  areligious studies.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  aunited states history.  aus history.  ayiddish.1 aAlpert, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, Walter Zev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobson, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirshenblatt-Gimblett, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoeffler, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLondon, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNetsky, Hankus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothstein, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSapoznik, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlobin, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlobin, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSvigals, Alicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo